<dl id="n12218d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12218d">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12218d"> 218(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> saliva <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12218d"> <li>FW proto </li><li><ms href="#n12218d">MS BL 47478-250</ms> </li><li>JJA 52:162 <a name="l42d" href="../../ff/fdra/lda.htm#l42d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/l/l42d.htm#n12218d">Draft: II.2&sect;4.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Nam sermo et loquela mea translata est in linguam alienam, sicut facile potest probari ex saliua scriptura mea <br><font color="green">[quotation from Saint Patrick&apos;s <cite>Confession</cite>: For my language and speech have been translated into a foreign tongue, as can be easily proved from the <mark>saliva</mark> [drivel]</font> of my writing] <small> Stefan Czarnowski, <a name="SCSP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SCSP"><cite title="source">Le culte des h&eacute;ros et ses conditions sociale: saint Patrick, h&eacute;ros nationale de l'Irlande</cite></a> (1919) 34n4</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: The translation here is an adaptation of that found in Charles H.H. Wright, <cite>The Writings of St. Patrick</cite> (London: Religious Tract Society, nd.), p. 49. Most modern translations render saliva less literally, as &lsquo;savour&rsquo; or &lsquo;flavour&rsquo;. </mm> </dd></dl>
